===6-sphere===
The [[n-sphere|6-sphere]] or hypersphere in seven-dimensional Euclidean space is the six-dimensional surface equidistant from a point, e.g. the origin. It has symbol {{math|''S<sup>6</sup>''}}, with formal definition for the 6-sphere with radius ''r'' of

:<math>S^6 = \left\{ x \in \mathbb{R}^7 : \|x\| = r\right\}.</math>

The volume of the space bounded by this 6-sphere is

: <math>V_7\,=\frac{16 \pi^3}{105}\,r^7</math>

which is 4.72477 × ''r''<sup>7</sup>, or 0.0369 of the [[7-cube]] that contains the 6-sphere.

==Applications==

===Cross product===

{{main|Seven-dimensional cross product}}
A cross product, that is a vector-valued, [[bilinear map|bilinear]], [[anticommutativity|anticommutative]] and [[orthogonality|orthogonal]] product of two vectors, is defined in seven dimensions. Along with the more usual [[cross product]] in three dimensions it is the only such product, except for trivial products.

===Exotic spheres===

{{main|Exotic sphere}}
In 1956, [[John Milnor]] constructed an [[exotic sphere]] in 7 dimensions and showed that there are at least 7 differentiable structures on the 7-sphere. In 1963 he showed that the exact number of such structures is 28.

